  <static seed="77" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/SubtractFractions10.pg">
    <statement><p>Subtract: <m>\displaystyle{\frac{3}{7} - \frac{37}{42}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-{\frac{19}{42}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To subtract two fractions with different denominators, we first have to find a common denominator.</p>
<p>In this case, the least common multiple of <m>7</m> and <m>42</m> is <m>42</m>.</p>
<p>Look at the first fraction <m>\displaystyle{\frac{3}{7}}</m>. To change the denominator to <m>42</m>, we multiply <m>6</m> at both the top and bottom, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \begin{aligned}\frac{3}{7} \amp = \frac{3 \cdot 6}{7 \cdot 6}\\ \amp = \frac{18}{42} \end{aligned}}</m></p>
<p>The second fraction already has the common denominator.</p>
<p>Finally, we can do the subtraction. The whole process is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{3}{7} - \frac{37}{42}
        \amp = \frac{18}{42} - \frac{37}{42} \\
        \amp = \frac{18 - 37}{42} \\
        \amp = -\frac{19}{42}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The answer is  <m>\displaystyle{-\frac{19}{42}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
